{"title_page": "Maude Apatow", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{short description|American actress and writer}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Maude Apatow\n| image        = Maude Apatow at SXSW Red Carpet premiere of BLOCKERS (39852920695) (cropped).jpg\n| caption      = Apatow at [[South by Southwest]] 2018\n| birth_name   = \n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1997|12|15}}\n| birth_place  = [[Los Banos, California]], U.S.\n| occupation   = Actress\n| years_active = 2005\u2013present\n| spouse       = \n| children     = \n| parents      = {{plainlist|\n* [[Leslie Mann]]\n* [[Judd Apatow]]\n}}\n| relatives    = [[Iris Apatow]] <small>(sister)</small>\n| residence    = \n}}\n\n'''Maude Apatow''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u00e6|p|\u0259|t|a\u028a}}; born December 15, 1997) is an American actress and writer. She is the elder daughter of director, producer, and screenwriter [[Judd Apatow]] and actress [[Leslie Mann]]. She rose to prominence for her roles as the daughter of her real-life mother's characters in her father's films ''[[Knocked Up]]'' (2007), ''[[Funny People]]'' (2009), and ''[[This Is 40]]'' (2012). Apatow then went on to appear in the films ''[[Other People (film)|Other People]]'' (2016), ''[[The House of Tomorrow (2017 film)|The House of Tomorrow]]'' (2017), and ''[[Assassination Nation]]'' (2018). In 2019, she began starring in the [[HBO]] drama series ''[[Euphoria (American TV series)|Euphoria]]''.\n\n== Early life and education ==\nApatow was born on December 15, 1997 in [[Los Banos, California]].<ref name=\"Heavy\">{{cite web|url=https://heavy.com/entertainment/2019/08/euphoria-cast-ages/|title='Euphoria' Cast Ages: How Old Are They in Real Life?|website=[[Heavy.com]]|last=Dwilson|first=Stephanie Dube|date=August 4, 2019|accessdate=August 14, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lazygirls.info/Maude_Apatow|title=Maude Apatow|website=Lazy Girls|accessdate=July 21, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619040131/http://www.lazygirls.info/Maude_Apatow|archive-date=July 29, 2019}}</ref> Her mother is actress [[Leslie Mann]] and her father is director, producer, and screenwriter [[Judd Apatow]], whose family is [[Jewish]]. Her maternal great-grandmother was of [[Finnish Americans|Finnish]] ancestry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://yle.fi/uutiset/cameron_diazin_tahdittamassa_komediassa_aitoa_suomalaista_sisua__videohaastattelu/7206746|title=Cameron Diazin t\u00e4hditt\u00e4m\u00e4ss\u00e4 komediassa aitoa suomalaista sisua \u2013 videohaastattelu|website=Yle Uutiset|language=fi|access-date=September 4, 2019}}</ref> She has a younger sister, [[Iris Apatow]], who is also an actress.<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/08/26/fashion/maude-apatow-is-growing-up-writing.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0|title=She's 14, Going on 140 Characters|website=[[The New York Times]]|last=LaPorte|first=Nicole|date=August 24, 2012|accessdate=July 21, 2013}}</ref> In high school, Apatow participated in musicals such as ''[[Cabaret (musical)|Cabaret]]'' and ''[[Into the Woods]]''. She studied theatre at [[Northwestern University]] in [[Evanston, Illinois]] but dropped out after her sophomore year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/style/2019/06/maude-apatow-caught-the-acting-bug-from-musicals|title=Maude Apatow Caught the Acting Bug From Musicals|website=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|last1=Hennemuth|first1=Britt|last2=Kim|first2=Sebastian|date=June 28, 2019|accessdate=August 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/tv/ct-ent-maude-apatow-northwestern-20181213-story.html|title=Actress Leslie Mann says daughter dropped out of Northwestern because 'it was really hard being in the cold'|website=[[Chicago Tribune]]|last=Swartz|first=Tracy|date=December 12, 2019|accessdate=August 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n=== Acting ===\nApatow began acting at the age of seven with a role in her father [[Judd Apatow]]'s 2005 film ''[[The 40-Year-Old Virgin]]'', though her scenes ultimately did not make the film's final cut.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/leslie-mann-reveals-husband-judd-12218772|title=Leslie Mann reveals she and husband Judd Apatow CUT their daughter out of The 40 Year Old Virgin on Lorraine|website=[[Daily Mirror]]|last=Desborough|first=Jenny|date=March 20, 2018|accessdate=August 7, 2019}}</ref> She then appeared in the 2007 film ''[[Knocked Up]]'', which was also written, produced, and directed by her father. She and her younger sister [[Iris Apatow]] played Sadie and Charlotte, respectively, the daughters of their real-life mother [[Leslie Mann]]'s character.<ref name=\"SCS\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cheatsheet.com/entertainment/judd-apatow-leslie-mann-daughter-maude-popular-show.html/|title=Judd Apatow and Leslie Mann's Daughter Is All Grown Up \u2014 What Popular Show Does She Star In?|website=Showbiz Cheat Sheet|last=Bleznak|first=Becca|date=August 3, 2019|accessdate=August 11, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.seventeen.com/celebrity/news/a32416/the-little-sisters-from-knocked-up-are-all-grown-up-you-have-to-see-what-they-look-like-now/|title=The Little Sisters from \"Knocked Up\" Are All Grown Up \u2014 You Have to See What They Look Like Now!|website=[[Seventeen (American magazine)|Seventeen]]|last=Rosa|first=Jelani Addams|date=July 16, 2015|accessdate=August 11, 2019}}</ref> She again appeared alongside her sister as the daughter of Mann's character in her father's 2009 film ''[[Funny People]]'', playing the role of Mable.<ref name=\"SCS\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.popsugar.com/entertainment/Who-Plays-Lexi-Euphoria-46285531|title=This Euphoria Actress Has 1 Very, Very Famous Family|website=[[PopSugar]]|last=Flynn|first=Caitlin|date=June 19, 2019|accessdate=August 11, 2019}}</ref> Apatow reprised her ''Knocked Up'' role in the 2012 spin-off sequel ''[[This Is 40]]'', starring Mann and [[Paul Rudd]]'s characters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/judd-apatow-casting-daughters-maude-393408|title=Judd Apatow on Casting His Daughters and Their Dramatic Onscreen Arguments|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|last=Zakarin|first=Jordan|date=November 20, 2012|accessdate=April 28, 2014}}</ref> For her performance in the film as Sadie, Apatow was nominated for the 2012 Phoenix Film Critics Society Award for Best Young Actress and the 2013 [[Young Artist Award]] for [[34th Young Artist Awards#Best Performance in a Feature Film&nbsp;\u2013 Supporting Young Actress|Best Performance in a Feature Film - Supporting Young Actress]].<ref name=\"PFCSA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2012/12/les-miserables-leads-phoenix-film-critics-nominations-42519/|title='Les Miserables' Leads Phoenix Film Critics Nominations|website=[[IndieWire]]|last=Knegt|first=Peter|date=December 12, 2012|accessdate=August 14, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"YAA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.youngartistawards.org/noms34.html|title=34th Annual Young Artist Awards|website=[[Young Artist Awards]]|accessdate=August 14, 2019|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6FaZ1wnUQ?|archivedate=April 2, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Apatow played an audience member in the film ''[[Pitch Perfect 2]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.etonline.com/movies/209097_exclusive_leslie_mann_on_the_best_hollywood_advice_she_given_her_daughter|title=EXCLUSIVE: Leslie Mann on the Best Hollywood Advice She's Given Her Daughter and Working With Robert De Niro|website=[[Entertainment Tonight]]|last=Tailor|first=Leena|date=January 31, 2017|accessdate=August 14, 2019}}</ref> That same year, she also recurred in the fourth season of the [[HBO]] series ''[[Girls (TV series)|Girls]]'' as Cleo. She appeared in three episodes of the series, which was executive produced by her father.<ref name=\"Heavy\" /><ref name=\"SCS\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvline.com/2014/07/23/maude-apatow-girls-season-4-cast-spoilers/|title=Girls Scoop: Judd Apatow's Daughter Guest-Starring in Season 4|website=[[TVLine]]|last=Swift|first=Andy|date=July 23, 2014|accessdate=August 14, 2019}}</ref> Apatow then appeared in the 2016 film ''[[Other People (film)|Other People]]'' as Alexandra Mulcahey.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/la-en-mn-molly-shannon-20161110-story.html|title=Death is complicated, says Molly Shannon, who finds its nuances in 'Other People'|website=[[Los Angeles Times]]|last=Ellwood|first=Gregory|date=November 10, 2016|accessdate=August 14, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instyle.com/news/judd-apatow-doting-dad-2016-sundance-festival|title=Judd Apatow Is the Most Doting Dad at Sundance 2016|website=[[InStyle]]|last=Clott Kanter|first=Sharon|date=January 22, 2016|accessdate=August 14, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eonline.com/news/733576/judd-apatow-s-daughter-maude-17-is-all-grown-up-brings-dad-to-2016-sundance-film-festival|title=Judd Apatow's Daughter Maude, 17, Is All Grown Up, Brings Dad to 2016 Sundance Film Festival|website=[[E! News]]|last=Heller|first=Corinne|date=January 23, 2016|accessdate=August 14, 2019}}</ref> In 2017, she played the role of Meredith Whitcomb in the film ''[[The House of Tomorrow (2017 film)|The House of Tomorrow]]'' and made her directorial debut with the short film ''Don't Mind Alice'', which she co-wrote and co-directed alongside [[Chip Rosenbloom#Personal life|Olivia Rosenbloom]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/the-house-of-tomorrow-film-review-asa-butterfield/|title='The House of Tomorrow' Film Review: Wry, Heartfelt Coming-of-Age Indie Mixes Buckminster Fuller and Punk|website=[[TheWrap]]|last=Abele|first=Robert|date=April 20, 2018|accessdate=August 14, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.etonline.com/judd-apatow-sweetly-gushes-over-daughter-maude-as-she-makes-directorial-debut-96170|title=Judd Apatow Sweetly Gushes Over Daughter Maude as She Makes Directorial Debut|website=[[Entertainment Tonight]]|last=Calvario|first=Liz|date=February 9, 2018|accessdate=August 14, 2019}}</ref> The following year in 2018, she starred as Grace in the film ''[[Assassination Nation]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/assassination-nation-bella-thorne-maude-apatow-joel-mchale-1201999863/|title=Bella Thorne, Maude Apatow, Joel McHale Join Thriller 'Assassination Nation'|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|last=McNary|first=Dave|date=March 1, 2017|accessdate=October 8, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wmagazine.com/story/assassination-nation-cast-explainer-odessa-young|title=A Complete Guide To the Cast of Assassination Nation|website=[[W (magazine)|W]]|last=Marine|first=Brooke|date=September 22, 2018|accessdate=August 15, 2019}}</ref> The film's director, [[Sam Levinson]], subsequently cast Apatow as a series regular in his HBO drama series, ''[[Euphoria (American TV series)|Euphoria]]'', which debuted in 2019. She plays Lexi Howard in the series, a role that Levinson wrote specifically for Apatow.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/07/euphoria-casting-directors-discover-zendaya-angus-cloud-hunter-schafer-new-stars-1202161635/|title='Euphoria': How the Casting Directors Discovered So Many Blazing Breakout Talents|website=[[IndieWire]]|last=Thompson|first=Anne|date=July 30, 2019|accessdate=August 15, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://collider.com/euphoria-storm-reid-maude-apatow-interview/|title='Euphoria': Storm Reid and Maude Apatow on Season 1's Lesson in Empathy|website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|last=Radish|first=Christina|date=August 8, 2019|accessdate=August 15, 2019}}</ref> She will next star in her father's and [[Pete Davidson]]'s upcoming 2020 film ''[[King of Staten Island]]'' as the sister of Davidson's character.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/maude-apatow-joins-pete-davidson-judd-apatow-comedy-1205947|title=Maude Apatow Joins Pete Davidson in Universal Comedy|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|last=Galuppo|first=Mia|date=April 30, 2019|accessdate=August 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Other ventures ===\nHaving joined [[Twitter]] in 2010, Apatow is noted to have a large online following, which helped her become a contributor to [[Zooey Deschanel]]'s website [[Hello Giggles]] as a writer and interviewer.<ref name=\"NYT\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.teenvogue.com/entertainment/2012-11/maude-apatow/?slide=1|title=Maude Apatow Explains How Twitter Changed Her Life|website=[[Teen Vogue]]|last=Lewis|first=Victoria|date=November 21, 2012|accessdate=April 28, 2014}}</ref> Her work on the site as well as her acting roles earned her a spot on the [[Forbes 30 Under 30|''Forbes'' 30 Under 30]] list in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/special-report/2012/30-under-30/30-under-30.html|title=30 Under 30: Entertainment|website=[[Forbes]]|last1=Howard|first1=Caroline|last2=Noer|first2=Michael|date=December 17, 2012|accessdate=April 28, 2014}}</ref> Apatow's Twitter account was named one of the \"Best Twitter Feeds of 2013\" by ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://techland.time.com/2013/03/25/140-best-twitter-feeds-of-2013/slide/maude-apatow/|title=The 140 Best Twitter Feeds of 2013|website=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|last=Lombard|first=Amy|date=March 20, 2013|accessdate=April 28, 2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140724112133/http://techland.time.com/2013/03/25/140-best-twitter-feeds-of-2013/slide/maude-apatow/|archive-date=July 24, 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n=== Film ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[The 40-Year-Old Virgin]]''\n| \n| Deleted scenes\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Knocked Up]]''\n| Sadie\n| \n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Funny People]]''\n| Mable\n| \n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[This Is 40]]''\n| Sadie\n| Reprised role from ''Knocked Up''\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Pitch Perfect 2]]''\n| Girl in audience\n| Extra\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Other People (film)|Other People]]''\n| Alexandra Mulcahey\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2017\n| ''[[The House of Tomorrow (2017 film)|The House of Tomorrow]]''\n| Meredith Whitcomb\n| \n|-\n| ''Don't Mind Alice''\n| \n| Short film; Also co-writer & co-director\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Assassination Nation]]''\n| Grace\n|-\n| 2020\n| ''[[King of Staten Island]]''\n| \n| ''Post-production''\n|}\n\n=== Television ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" |Notes\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Girls (TV series)|Girls]]''\n| Cleo\n| Recurring role (3 episodes)\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Euphoria (American TV series)|Euphoria]]''\n| Lexi Howard\n| Series regular\n|-\n| 2020\n| ''[[Hollywood (American TV series)|Hollywood]]''\n| Henrietta\n| Upcoming limited series \n|}\n\n== Accolades ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Award\n! Category\n! Work\n! Result\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Ref.\n|-\n| 2012\n| Phoenix Film Critics Society Award\n| Best Young Actress\n| rowspan=\"2\" | ''[[This Is 40]]''\n| {{nom}}\n| align=\"center\" | <ref name=\"PFCSA\" />\n|-\n| 2013\n| [[Young Artist Award]]\n| [[34th Young Artist Awards#Best Performance in a Feature Film&nbsp;\u2013 Supporting Young Actress|Best Performance in a Feature Film - Supporting Young Actress]]\n| {{nom}}\n| align=\"center\" | <ref name=\"YAA\" />\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{commons category-inline|Maude Apatow}}\n* {{Twitter|maudeapatow}}\n* {{IMDb name|nm2654829}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Apatow, Maude}}\n[[Category:1997 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:American child actresses]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American people of Finnish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:Film child actresses]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Northwestern University alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{short description|American actress and writer}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Maude Apatow\n| image        = Maude Apatow at SXSW Red Carpet premiere of BLOCKERS (39852920695) (cropped).jpg\n| caption      = Apatow at [[South by Southwest]] 2018\n| birth_name   = \n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1997|12|15}}\n| birth_place  = [[Los Banos, California]], U.S.\n| occupation   = Actress\n| years_active = 2005\u2013present\n| spouse       = \n| children     = \n| parents      = {{plainlist|\n* [[Leslie Mann]]\n* [[Judd Apatow]]\n}}\n| relatives    = [[Iris Apatow]] <small>(sister)</small>\n| residence    = \n}}\n\n'''Maude Apatow''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u00e6|p|\u0259|t|a\u028a}}; born December 15, 1997) is an American actress and writer. She is the elder daughter of director, producer, and screenwriter [[Judd Apatow]] and actress [[Leslie Mann]]. She rose to prominence for her roles as the daughter of her real-life mother's characters in her father's films ''[[Knocked Up]]'' (2007), ''[[Funny People]]'' (2009), and ''[[This Is 40]]'' (2012). Apatow then went on to appear in the films ''[[Other People (film)|Other People]]'' (2016), ''[[The House of Tomorrow (2017 film)|The House of Tomorrow]]'' (2017), and ''[[Assassination Nation]]'' (2018). In 2019, she began starring in the [[HBO]] drama series ''[[Euphoria (American TV series)|Euphoria]]''.\n\n== Early life and education ==\nApatow was born on December 15, 1997 in [[Los Banos, California]].<ref name=\"Heavy\">{{cite web|url=https://heavy.com/entertainment/2019/08/euphoria-cast-ages/|title='Euphoria' Cast Ages: How Old Are They in Real Life?|website=[[Heavy.com]]|last=Dwilson|first=Stephanie Dube|date=August 4, 2019|accessdate=August 14, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lazygirls.info/Maude_Apatow|title=Maude Apatow|website=Lazy Girls|accessdate=July 21, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619040131/http://www.lazygirls.info/Maude_Apatow|archive-date=July 29, 2019}}</ref> Her mother is actress [[Leslie Mann]] and her father is director, producer, and screenwriter [[Judd Apatow]], whose family is [[Jewish]]. Her maternal great-grandmother was of [[Finnish Americans|Finnish]] ancestry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://yle.fi/uutiset/cameron_diazin_tahdittamassa_komediassa_aitoa_suomalaista_sisua__videohaastattelu/7206746|title=Cameron Diazin t\u00e4hditt\u00e4m\u00e4ss\u00e4 komediassa aitoa suomalaista sisua \u2013 videohaastattelu|website=Yle Uutiset|language=fi|access-date=September 4, 2019}}</ref> She has a younger sister, [[Iris Apatow]], who is also an actress.<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/08/26/fashion/maude-apatow-is-growing-up-writing.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0|title=She's 14, Going on 140 Characters|website=[[The New York Times]]|last=LaPorte|first=Nicole|date=August 24, 2012|accessdate=July 21, 2013}}</ref> In high school, Apatow participated in musicals such as ''[[Cabaret (musical)|Cabaret]]'' and ''[[Into the Woods]]''. She studied theatre at [[Northwestern University]] in [[Evanston, Illinois]] but dropped out after her sophomore year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/style/2019/06/maude-apatow-caught-the-acting-bug-from-musicals|title=Maude Apatow Caught the Acting Bug From Musicals|website=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|last1=Hennemuth|first1=Britt|last2=Kim|first2=Sebastian|date=June 28, 2019|accessdate=August 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/tv/ct-ent-maude-apatow-northwestern-20181213-story.html|title=Actress Leslie Mann says daughter dropped out of Northwestern because 'it was really hard being in the cold'|website=[[Chicago Tribune]]|last=Swartz|first=Tracy|date=December 12, 2019|accessdate=August 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n=== Acting ===\nApatow began acting at the age of seven with a role in her father [[Judd Apatow]]'s 2005 film ''[[The 40-Year-Old Virgin]]'', though her scenes ultimately did not make the film's final cut.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/leslie-mann-reveals-husband-judd-12218772|title=Leslie Mann reveals she and husband Judd Apatow CUT their daughter out of The 40 Year Old Virgin on Lorraine|website=[[Daily Mirror]]|last=Desborough|first=Jenny|date=March 20, 2018|accessdate=August 7, 2019}}</ref> She then appeared in the 2007 film ''[[Knocked Up]]'', which was also written, produced, and directed by her father. She and her younger sister [[Iris Apatow]] played Sadie and Charlotte, respectively, the daughters of their real-life mother [[Leslie Mann]]'s character.<ref name=\"SCS\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cheatsheet.com/entertainment/judd-apatow-leslie-mann-daughter-maude-popular-show.html/|title=Judd Apatow and Leslie Mann's Daughter Is All Grown Up \u2014 What Popular Show Does She Star In?|website=Showbiz Cheat Sheet|last=Bleznak|first=Becca|date=August 3, 2019|accessdate=August 11, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.seventeen.com/celebrity/news/a32416/the-little-sisters-from-knocked-up-are-all-grown-up-you-have-to-see-what-they-look-like-now/|title=The Little Sisters from \"Knocked Up\" Are All Grown Up \u2014 You Have to See What They Look Like Now!|website=[[Seventeen (American magazine)|Seventeen]]|last=Rosa|first=Jelani Addams|date=July 16, 2015|accessdate=August 11, 2019}}</ref> She again appeared alongside her sister as the daughter of Mann's character in her father's 2009 film ''[[Funny People]]'', playing the role of Mable.<ref name=\"SCS\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.popsugar.com/entertainment/Who-Plays-Lexi-Euphoria-46285531|title=This Euphoria Actress Has 1 Very, Very Famous Family|website=[[PopSugar]]|last=Flynn|first=Caitlin|date=June 19, 2019|accessdate=August 11, 2019}}</ref> Apatow reprised her ''Knocked Up'' role in the 2012 spin-off sequel ''[[This Is 40]]'', starring Mann and [[Paul Rudd]]'s characters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/judd-apatow-casting-daughters-maude-393408|title=Judd Apatow on Casting His Daughters and Their Dramatic Onscreen Arguments|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|last=Zakarin|first=Jordan|date=November 20, 2012|accessdate=April 28, 2014}}</ref> For her performance in the film as Sadie, Apatow was nominated for the 2012 Phoenix Film Critics Society Award for Best Young Actress and the 2013 [[Young Artist Award]] for [[34th Young Artist Awards#Best Performance in a Feature Film&nbsp;\u2013 Supporting Young Actress|Best Performance in a Feature Film - Supporting Young Actress]].<ref name=\"PFCSA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2012/12/les-miserables-leads-phoenix-film-critics-nominations-42519/|title='Les Miserables' Leads Phoenix Film Critics Nominations|website=[[IndieWire]]|last=Knegt|first=Peter|date=December 12, 2012|accessdate=August 14, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"YAA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.youngartistawards.org/noms34.html|title=34th Annual Young Artist Awards|website=[[Young Artist Awards]]|accessdate=August 14, 2019|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6FaZ1wnUQ?|archivedate=April 2, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Apatow played an audience member in the film ''[[Pitch Perfect 2]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.etonline.com/movies/209097_exclusive_leslie_mann_on_the_best_hollywood_advice_she_given_her_daughter|title=EXCLUSIVE: Leslie Mann on the Best Hollywood Advice She's Given Her Daughter and Working With Robert De Niro|website=[[Entertainment Tonight]]|last=Tailor|first=Leena|date=January 31, 2017|accessdate=August 14, 2019}}</ref> That same year, she also recurred in the fourth season of the [[HBO]] series ''[[Girls (TV series)|Girls]]'' as Cleo. She appeared in three episodes of the series, which was executive produced by her father.<ref name=\"Heavy\" /><ref name=\"SCS\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvline.com/2014/07/23/maude-apatow-girls-season-4-cast-spoilers/|title=Girls Scoop: Judd Apatow's Daughter Guest-Starring in Season 4|website=[[TVLine]]|last=Swift|first=Andy|date=July 23, 2014|accessdate=August 14, 2019}}</ref> Apatow then appeared in the 2016 film ''[[Other People (film)|Other People]]'' as Alexandra Mulcahey.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/la-en-mn-molly-shannon-20161110-story.html|title=Death is complicated, says Molly Shannon, who finds its nuances in 'Other People'|website=[[Los Angeles Times]]|last=Ellwood|first=Gregory|date=November 10, 2016|accessdate=August 14, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instyle.com/news/judd-apatow-doting-dad-2016-sundance-festival|title=Judd Apatow Is the Most Doting Dad at Sundance 2016|website=[[InStyle]]|last=Clott Kanter|first=Sharon|date=January 22, 2016|accessdate=August 14, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eonline.com/news/733576/judd-apatow-s-daughter-maude-17-is-all-grown-up-brings-dad-to-2016-sundance-film-festival|title=Judd Apatow's Daughter Maude, 17, Is All Grown Up, Brings Dad to 2016 Sundance Film Festival|website=[[E! News]]|last=Heller|first=Corinne|date=January 23, 2016|accessdate=August 14, 2019}}</ref> In 2017, she played the role of Meredith Whitcomb in the film ''[[The House of Tomorrow (2017 film)|The House of Tomorrow]]'' and made her directorial debut with the short film ''Don't Mind Alice'', which she co-wrote and co-directed alongside [[Chip Rosenbloom#Personal life|Olivia Rosenbloom]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/the-house-of-tomorrow-film-review-asa-butterfield/|title='The House of Tomorrow' Film Review: Wry, Heartfelt Coming-of-Age Indie Mixes Buckminster Fuller and Punk|website=[[TheWrap]]|last=Abele|first=Robert|date=April 20, 2018|accessdate=August 14, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.etonline.com/judd-apatow-sweetly-gushes-over-daughter-maude-as-she-makes-directorial-debut-96170|title=Judd Apatow Sweetly Gushes Over Daughter Maude as She Makes Directorial Debut|website=[[Entertainment Tonight]]|last=Calvario|first=Liz|date=February 9, 2018|accessdate=August 14, 2019}}</ref> The following year in 2018, she starred as Grace in the film ''[[Assassination Nation]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/assassination-nation-bella-thorne-maude-apatow-joel-mchale-1201999863/|title=Bella Thorne, Maude Apatow, Joel McHale Join Thriller 'Assassination Nation'|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|last=McNary|first=Dave|date=March 1, 2017|accessdate=October 8, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wmagazine.com/story/assassination-nation-cast-explainer-odessa-young|title=A Complete Guide To the Cast of Assassination Nation|website=[[W (magazine)|W]]|last=Marine|first=Brooke|date=September 22, 2018|accessdate=August 15, 2019}}</ref> The film's director, [[Sam Levinson]], subsequently cast Apatow as a series regular in his HBO drama series, ''[[Euphoria (American TV series)|Euphoria]]'', which debuted in 2019. She plays Lexi Howard in the series, a role that Levinson wrote specifically for Apatow.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/07/euphoria-casting-directors-discover-zendaya-angus-cloud-hunter-schafer-new-stars-1202161635/|title='Euphoria': How the Casting Directors Discovered So Many Blazing Breakout Talents|website=[[IndieWire]]|last=Thompson|first=Anne|date=July 30, 2019|accessdate=August 15, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://collider.com/euphoria-storm-reid-maude-apatow-interview/|title='Euphoria': Storm Reid and Maude Apatow on Season 1's Lesson in Empathy|website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|last=Radish|first=Christina|date=August 8, 2019|accessdate=August 15, 2019}}</ref> She will next star in her father's and [[Pete Davidson]]'s upcoming 2020 film ''[[King of Staten Island]]'' as the sister of Davidson's character.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/maude-apatow-joins-pete-davidson-judd-apatow-comedy-1205947|title=Maude Apatow Joins Pete Davidson in Universal Comedy|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|last=Galuppo|first=Mia|date=April 30, 2019|accessdate=August 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Other ventures ===\nHaving joined [[Twitter]] in 2010, Apatow is noted to have a large online following, which helped her become a contributor to [[Zooey Deschanel]]'s website [[Hello Giggles]] as a writer and interviewer.<ref name=\"NYT\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.teenvogue.com/entertainment/2012-11/maude-apatow/?slide=1|title=Maude Apatow Explains How Twitter Changed Her Life|website=[[Teen Vogue]]|last=Lewis|first=Victoria|date=November 21, 2012|accessdate=April 28, 2014}}</ref> Her work on the site as well as her acting roles earned her a spot on the [[Forbes 30 Under 30|''Forbes'' 30 Under 30]] list in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/special-report/2012/30-under-30/30-under-30.html|title=30 Under 30: Entertainment|website=[[Forbes]]|last1=Howard|first1=Caroline|last2=Noer|first2=Michael|date=December 17, 2012|accessdate=April 28, 2014}}</ref> Apatow's Twitter account was named one of the \"Best Twitter Feeds of 2013\" by ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://techland.time.com/2013/03/25/140-best-twitter-feeds-of-2013/slide/maude-apatow/|title=The 140 Best Twitter Feeds of 2013|website=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|last=Lombard|first=Amy|date=March 20, 2013|accessdate=April 28, 2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140724112133/http://techland.time.com/2013/03/25/140-best-twitter-feeds-of-2013/slide/maude-apatow/|archive-date=July 24, 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n=== Film ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[The 40-Year-Old Virgin]]''\n| \n| Deleted scenes\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Knocked Up]]''\n| Sadie\n| \n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Funny People]]''\n| Mable\n| \n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[This Is 40]]''\n| Sadie\n| Reprised role from ''Knocked Up''\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Pitch Perfect 2]]''\n| Girl in audience\n| Extra\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Other People (film)|Other People]]''\n| Alexandra Mulcahey\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2017\n| ''[[The House of Tomorrow (2017 film)|The House of Tomorrow]]''\n| Meredith Whitcomb\n| \n|-\n| ''Don't Mind Alice''\n| \n| Short film; Also co-writer & co-director\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Assassination Nation]]''\n| Grace\n|-\n| 2020\n| ''[[King of Staten Island]]''\n| \n| ''Post-production''\n|}\n\n=== Television ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" |Notes\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Girls (TV series)|Girls]]''\n| Cleo\n| Recurring role (3 episodes)\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Euphoria (American TV series)|Euphoria]]''\n| Lexi Howard\n| Series regular\n|-\n| 2020\n| ''[[Hollywood (American TV series)|Hollywood]]''\n| Henrietta\n| Upcoming limited series \n|}\n\n== Accolades ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Award\n! Category\n! Work\n! Result\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Ref.\n|-\n| 2012\n| Phoenix Film Critics Society Award\n| Best Young Actress\n| rowspan=\"2\" | ''[[This Is 40]]''\n| {{nom}}\n| align=\"center\" | <ref name=\"PFCSA\" />\n|-\n| 2013\n| [[Young Artist Award]]\n| [[34th Young Artist Awards#Best Performance in a Feature Film&nbsp;\u2013 Supporting Young Actress|Best Performance in a Feature Film - Supporting Young Actress]]\n| {{nom}}\n| align=\"center\" | <ref name=\"YAA\" />\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{commons category-inline|Maude Apatow}}\n* {{Twitter|maudeapatow}}\n* {{IMDb name|nm2654829}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Apatow, Maude}}\n[[Category:1997 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:American child actresses]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American people of Finnish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:Film child actresses]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Northwestern University alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maude_